post_text:
Parents please fill out the COVID form whether your child is attending today or not, this will help us make adjustments for attendance, activities, arrivals, and dismissals.

For those attending today, please go to our website/app and fill out the form online by 8am. If you have difficulty logging in you should have 5 paper forms that was located in your welcome back packet; this form is to be presented to staff or Mr. Palombo upon arrival.

No student or staff member will be allowed in the building if the form is not completed.

Any questions or concerns please contact the the CMCES office at (609) 884 8485 between the hours of 8am and 4pm.

Thank you for your anticipated and continued cooperation and support in ensuring that our students, staff, and school remains safe.

post_text: Mr. Palombo would like to thank everyone for their support! Quite a memorable first Principal's Appreciation Day for him!
text: Mr. Palombo would like to thank everyone for their support! Quite a memorable first Principal's Appreciation Day for him!

post_text:
Today is Principal Appreciation Day!
Much of our success during this unique time would be all for naught without the support & leadership of our principal, Mr. Palombo who has gone above & beyond the responsibilities relinquished to a principal. He not only goes to the building each and every day, he hands out meals to all the families that need them, he's beyond supportive of the teachers (calling student's parents when teachers are not able to reach them), he is beyond flexible, and he interacts with students via his VIMEO announcements, ZOOM & Google classroom sessions. We are beyond grateful and want to give credit where credit is long overdue. THANK YOU, Mr. Palombo!

shared_text:
Alliance for New Jersey Environmental Education ( anjee )
April 23 at 2:52 PM ·

The U.S. Department of Education announced today that Cape May City Elementary School in Cape May City, NJ and Readington Middle School in Readington Township, NJ are among the 2020 U.S. Department of Education Green Ribbon Schools award honorees.

Both schools were nominated by the New Jersey Department of Education for reduction in environmental impact and costs; improved health and wellness of schools, students and staff; and environmental and sustainability education integrated throughout their curriculum. Huge Congrats from all of your friends at ANJEE!

Garden State Teachers to Give Lessons on
New Jersey Public Television

Starting Monday, April 6, children throughout New Jersey will be able to tune into NJTV, New Jersey’s public television network, for NJTV Learning Live, a program featuring lessons taught by New Jersey teachers. The initiative, designed to advance learning during the statewide school closures caused by the COVID19 pandemic, was created through a partnership between NJTV, the New Jersey Education Association
(NJEA) and the New Jersey Department of Education (NJDOE)

Starting Monday, April 6, children throughout New Jersey will be able to tune into NJTV, New Jersey’s public television network, for NJTV Learning Live, a program featuring lessons taught by New Jersey teachers. The initiative, designed to advance learning during the statewide school closures caused by the COVID19 pandemic, was created through a partnership between NJTV, the New Jersey Education Association
(NJEA) and the New Jersey Department of Education (NJDOE)

Blow Bubbles for Autism (April 2nd 2020)

For several years, Cape May City Elementary has participated in this activity to recognize World Autism Awareness Day. Bubbles are symbols of joy, hope and laughter. They bring people together. When we Blow Bubbles for Autism together, we create a new awareness of families facing autism. Cape May City Elementary would like to continue our tradition this year, even though we cannot be together, so please take a moment to celebrate and blow some bubbles!

PLEASE share your pictures of your students blowing bubbles for Autism!! We'd love to see them!

post_text: Parents and students as we continue through these difficult and frustrating times, there are quite a few interesting things going on here at Cape May City Elementary (virtually) that you can check out and participate in via our Facebook page! A reminder to parents please check your emails periodically as teachers will be in constant contact with you. Also if you recently changed your email address please reach out to your child’s teacher as we are in the process of rolling out new digital platforms over the next week to ensure that your child’s educational development is on going. Our teachers are excited to try something new with our students and hope to see them participating, so please stay tuned to your emails as we move away from paper and pencil, towards more integration of technology. Should you have any questions or concerns please know that you can contact Mr. Palombo at zpalombo@cmcboe.org or at 609.884.8485 x226 during the regular school hours. Stay healthy and well!

post_text:
Good Morning Parents and Students,

This is Mr. Garguilo with an important update:

“As we move into week two of the school closure, I can inform you that we will be closed until further notice. We are waiting for direction from Governor Phil Murphy. We realize last week was a challenge for all of us, you as parents and teachers. Moving forward we have taken some of the suggestions from you and we are going to modify our instruction. We are looking to redefine our approach and interactivity. It is important that we not only educate your children but also make them feel safe and supported during this difficult time. As always our staff, administration and counselor are there to assist you. Thank you.”
text:
Good Morning Parents and Students,

This is Mr. Garguilo with an important update:

“As we move into week two of the school closure, I can inform you that we will be closed until further notice. We are waiting for direction from Governor Phil Murphy. We realize last week was a challenge for all of us, you as parents and teachers. Moving forward we have taken some of the suggestions from you and we are going to modify our instruction. We are looking to redefine our approach and interactivity. It is important that we not only educate your children but also make them feel safe and supported during this difficult time. As always our staff, administration and counselor are there to assist you. Thank you.”

Dear Cape May City Elementary School Families,

Tomorrow morning, September 26, 2019, we wanted to make you aware that we are a “hero marker stop” for the NJ Run for the Fallen. Please expect more people than usual on our school property including police personnel.

If you are dropping off your child, please do so in a timely manner. The event begins shortly after school starts, so please do not linger after dropping off your child. Busses will be operating as normal.

Thank you for your cooperation!

post_text: On Wednesday, May 29, 2019, Cape May City Elementary honored all those that have volunteered out of the kindness of their heart with a breakfast, organized by Leah McClure and Nicole Cooper (volunteer coordinators). Each year, they recognize an outstanding volunteer for their hard work and dedication to helping our students and our community. This year we acknowledge Betty Ferrante for her countless hours of volunteering her time throughout the year, across the board at various events and Terry McGarvey, accepting this award on behalf of Our Lady Star of the Sea. Volunteers – they don’t necessarily have the time but they have the heart.

post_text:
We are having our annual blood drive on Wednesday, March 6th, 2-7pm.
The Red Cross is behind on donations by 20,000 units! That's a huge deficit. So please, if you can, donate.
Save time and schedule your appointment by visiting redcrossblood.org (sponsor code: capemayschool), or download the free Red Cross blood donor app. Our goal is 27 donors. So far we have 4 signed up. Walk-ins are welcome, thought they strongly recommend making an appointment.

Thank you for your help!

post_text:
What an absolute honor and privilege for our school to be a stop along the Run for the Fallen Heroes recognizing and paying tribute to the men and women lost during their line of service in our Armed Forces. Today, we were bestowed with the honor of recognizing Lance Cpl. Curtis A. Christensen, Jr., who lost his life Jan .11, 2008, defending and serving our country. 3rd - 6th Grade students lined up the front walkway cheering on the runners who came up to the flag post to meet and greet Mrs. Christensen and thanking the sacrifice her son and her family made. It was a touching morning to say the least and one that the students will remember for a long time to come.
We hope we can be part of this honorable event for years to come.
